-- Commodities Drop Most in Three Weeks on Greek Bailout Concern
-- B y   M a r i o   P a r k e r
-- 2012-02-10T19:35:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-10/commodities-drop-most-in-three-weeks-on-greek-bailout-concern.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI Index of
24 commodities tumbled the most in three weeks, led by declines
in gold, copper and crude oil, on concern that a Greek bailout
plan was may unravel.  The index slipped 1 percent to 673.91 as of 1:28 p.m.  New
York , the steepest decline since Jan. 20, after Luxembourg Prime
Minister  Jean-Claude Juncker , chairman of the group of euro-area
finance chiefs, said  Greece  won’t get financial aid until it
implements an austerity plan.  “It’s just negative news,” said  Dan Flynn , a trader at
PFGBest in Chicago. “The market’s looking at what’s going on in
Greece and saying it’s a negative. It’s just a bad Friday.”  Gold futures for April delivery dropped 0.9 percent to
$1,725.30 an ounce on the Comex in New York. The contract has
climbed 9.9 percent this year.  Copper futures for March delivery fell 11.65 cents, or 2.9
percent, to $3.862 a pound on the Comex, heading for the biggest
decline since Dec. 14.  Crude oil for March delivery declined $1.23, or 1.2
percent, to $98.61 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange ,
the steepest decline since Feb. 2. Futures have dropped 0.2
percent this year.  Gasoline for March delivery fell 4.23 cents, or 1.4
percent, to $2.9705 a gallon in New York, the biggest drop since
Jan. 30.  To contact the reporter on this story:
